##Why are Japanese, Americans and Australians rushing for toilet paper in the face of an epidemic?

Micro Signal China Business Journal

Function introduction, grow in step with Chinese enterprises, talk with business leaders, spread business ideals, serve business people, "China Business News" control of the absolute voice of Chinese business.

With the continued global spread of NCP, cases are now confirmed on all continents except Antarctica. As of 19:00 Beijing Time on March 2,65 countries and regions except China have reported more than 9,000 confirmed cases of NCP.

Who director-general Tan Desai announced on February 28, the new pneumonia epidemic global risk level from the previous "high" to "very high.

In the early days of the outbreak, a shortage of face masks caused panic buying at home and abroad. However, with the gradual improvement of China's epidemic prevention and control situation and the massive release of domestic production capacity, masks in China's domestic market are no longer hard to find. However, in countries such as South Korea and Italy, where a large number of newly confirmed cases have emerged, face masks are still in short supply.

But as the epidemic spread across more countries, a bizarre phenomenon began to appear -- as people in Japan, the United States, Australia and other countries poured into supermarkets to buy and store up supplies for daily use, one of the most iconic products is toilet paper.

The NHK reported that Kumamoto was out of stock of toilet paper, tissues and other daily necessities as people rushed to buy them. Some shops also posted signs in the toilet paper area saying, "you can only buy one per person. ".

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
PHOTOGRAPH: Xinhua

Fake News Triggers Toilet Paper Rush

According to the Ministry of Health, Labour and Welfare, as of 10:30 GMT, 1 March, a total of 947 people had been diagnosed with NCP in Japan, of whom 228 were infected in Japan and had travelled from China to Japan, the number of confirmed cases on the diamond princess cruise ship was 705, while 14 people returned home on chartered flights.

After the epidemic spread to Japan, as a necessary epidemic mask is not immediately urgent, the Japanese people suddenly began to scramble for Toilet Paper, supermarkets, pharmacies and other places of toilet paper are "snapped up. ".

According to the Shangguan News report, a search for "toilet paper" on Japanese social media will pop up false information such as "raw materials can not be imported from China" and "It is difficult for Japan to produce toilet paper" , unbeknownst to them, Japanese are piling into supermarkets to "stock up like crazy" .

In the rush to buy, some have succeeded, posting "trophies" on social media, while others have failed to do so, facing "empty shelves" with regret.

The prime minister has even been alarmed by the Japanese hoarding of Toilet Paper. Japanese Prime Minister Shinzo Abe held a press conference on February 29, on the Japanese government in the epidemic prevention measures to explain to the Japanese people.

Anbe said production of 600m masks a month would be achieved in March to ensure supplies. He also stressed that for commodities like toilet paper, Japan's domestic production can fully meet market demand, and stocks are very high, there is no shortage of supplies, so please buy calmly.

If you think that Japan's Toilet Paper Hoarding is a fluke, it is a storm in a teacup, you are wrong. Because the United States and Australia also began to ignite a rush to buy toilet paper.

Toilet paper for first time in US supermarket

A state of emergency has been declared in Washington state since the spread of the COVID-19 in the United States. As the outbreak escalated, Americans began to stock up.

At a large supermarket south of Seattle in Washington State last weekend, customers lined up to shop, many with hand sanitizer and hand sanitizer in their shopping carts, local media reported, and medical masks and toilet paper are sold out.

A similar situation has occurred in supermarkets in Oregon. Worried shoppers swarmed the stores, emptying them of toilet paper, tissues, bottled water, snacks, canned goods and more.

"Toilet paper is as precious as gold when disaster strikes, " said one customer, while staff said it was the first time in the supermarket's history that toilet paper had been sold out.

At a supermarket in southern San Francisco, California, more than 500 customers flooded in within 30 minutes of opening, wiping out all bottled water and toilet paper within hours.

A customer took photos of empty shelves and posted them on social media, "New crown pneumonia is driving everyone crazy. I've never seen so many people in a supermarket, more than on Black Friday, " the caption read. "bottles of water, toilet paper, meat and many other items have been looted. "

Toilet paper hoarding has also hit Australia, New Zealand and other countries. The reporter noticed on the micro-blog that many micro-blog users located in Australia had posted the photos.

In Australia, there have been two more confirmed cases from Iran in the past few days, and as a result, supermarkets have been sold out, starting with toilet paper and canned food..

Japan's Shinsendo Pharmacy Store Manager Morayama told the media, general shops after noon can no longer buy toilet paper, while others take advantage of this temporary shortage of toilet paper in the secondary market for high-priced reselling. When the shop assistant asks the customer why to rush to buy toilet paper, the other side basically says is to see on the network with new crown pneumonia related hearsay, worry about daily necessities shortage and come to stock up.

It turned out that Japanese social media was circulating on the Internet: "Toilet Paper and face masks are made of the same material, whereas toilet paper is made in China, so there will be a shortage of toilet paper and paper products, so it's better to buy them in advance. "

The reporter noticed that Japanese officials had come out to dispel rumors about the dependence of raw materials on imports. Japan's domestic toilet paper and face masks are not made from the same material and do not rely on imports from China, the Japan Household Paper Industry Association said in a statement. At present, 98 percent of toilet paper is made in Japan and there will be no shortage as long as there is no panic buying.

Japan's Ministry of Economy, Trade and industry also refuted the rumors, and urged the Japanese people to remain calm, do not believe the rumors, normal procurement of living materials can make toilet paper back to normal production and sales track.

In an interview with reporters, Zhao Ping, director of the International Trade Research Department at the China Council for the Promotion of trade, said that both Japan and the United States have relatively complete industrial chains for the production of toilet paper, it is therefore unlikely that a shortage of raw materials will affect the supply of materials. "As long as there is no large-scale panic buying, there is no problem to meet the daily supply of toilet paper. "

The United States leads the world in toilet paper consumption per capita

Li Hui (not her real name) , a graduate student in the United States, told reporters that there were some differences between Americans and Chinese in cleaning habits.

"When we clean our kitchen or bathroom, we like to use rags, but Americans are less likely to recycle rags and more likely to use toilet paper or disposable paper towels to clean. "

American consumers use about three rolls of toilet paper a week, about a fifth of the world's total, according to the environmental group the Earth and Natural Resources Defense Council.

The report says disposable tissues such as toilet paper used in the United States are made from wood pulp, mostly from virgin forests in northern Canada, canadian logging companies cut down more than 1 million acres, or 405,000 hectares, of forest each year.

The United States consumes 141 rolls of toilet paper a year, ranking first in the world, while Japan ranks fourth, consuming 91 rolls a year, according to a report by two major environmental groups.

Low e-commerce penetration may be the trigger

After the outbreak of new crown pneumonia in China, most consumers can easily buy what they need through shopping websites, despite the impact on people's purchasing of daily necessities. But for consumers in other countries, it may not be so easy.

Despite the abundance of goods in Japanese supermarkets, e commerce is Market penetration compared with China, Zhao Ping said in an interview, as if Japan's online retail sales accounted for less than 10% of total retail sales. The low penetration rate of E-COMMERCE, goods distribution chain is not perfect, it may be the incentive for consumers to hoard toilet paper and other household goods.

"Moreover, the distribution cost of goods bought online in Japan is very high, and the distribution time is relatively long. For products such as toilet paper and rice, which are big in size and low in unit price, the distribution cost may even exceed the price of the goods themselves, so most Japanese people prefer to shop in supermarkets, " Zhao Ping said.

China's online retail sales accounted for 18.4 percent of the total retail sales of consumer goods in 2018, according to the China Internet Industry Development Trend and Prosperity Index Report (2019) released by the China Information and Communications Research Institute, it has become the world's highest penetration market for E-commerce, 6.4 percentage points higher than second-place South Korea.

According to the United States Department of Commerce, U.S. E commerce retail sales accounted for about 11 percent of total retail sales in 2019, up from 9.9 percent in 2018; U.S. e commerce sales grew 14.9 percent in 2019, up from 13.6 percent in the same period in 2018.

In the fourth quarter of 2019, US e-commerce retail sales grew 16.4 per cent year-on-year to $187bn, unseasonally adjusted, and to $602bn for the year as a whole, double the level of five years earlier.
